Some surprising hostility* for a writefag advice topic. While I'd agree that studying writing planning, arc creation, world building, and stylistic writing are all important, at some point you do just need to put pen to paper.

Just like committing a story to print, you're not going to figure out what issues you have until you get something out of your head and onto the page. It's absolutely imperative if you're going to find out what your own weaknesses are, what your strengths are, and what you personally don't like about your own work. Knowing where - specifically - you need to improve makes a big difference in how much you get out of all the storycrafting research you're recommending.
